text: Isaiah Mustafa (old spice) is Mike?  Look at the trailer, now to this comment, now back to the trailer. It’s Bill on a bike, with Bev. Now back to the comment (sorry, Team Ben members) Now back to the trailer. Ooh, it’s Pennywise but don’t look into the dead lights. Cut to black, the teens are now adults. And with them come new actors. Look closely, it’s James McAvoy, but alas not bald like Charles Xavier nor pretending to have 22 personalities (want a PB and J?) Look again, it’s Jessica Chastain, gone from running from an abusive dad, to running from a naked grandma (No, Steve Harvey). Look again, it’s Finn Wolfhard, blink again, now he’s Bill Hader. text: (Spoiler if hasn't read the book)  0:22 to 0:33 - Adrian Mellon, a young gay character, 3 homophobic throw Adrian over a bridge after hurt him, pennywise drags him out of the water, bites into his armpit and cracks his ribs  1:44 - In the book Don Hagarty is the life partner of Adrian Mellon, he sees pennywise with Adrian then balloons floated against the underside of the bridge, and printed on the side of each was I ♡ Derry  1:57 - When Mike calls Stan to tell him that It had returned to Derry and that they would all have to come back to fight it,  after the phone call, he tells his wife that he is going to take a bath. His wife, Patty, insists that she was going to scrub him, therefore going to check on him. There, she sees that he cut his wrists in shape of T. With his own blood, he writes the word IT on the bathroom wall  2:11 - Eddie is killed  by It, It bites Eddie's arm off. With his few remaining seconds, he tells Richie to stop calling him Eds, before dying. The Losers later leave Eddie’s body in the sewers, despite Richie's protests saying they should take his body back with them. He kissed Eddie's cheek before leaving.  Eddies death impacted Richie the most

text: ) In May 2019, members of the Minnesota House of Representatives and the Minnesota Senate sent official letters to the Minnesota Medical Association (MMA) expressing concern over forced organ harvesting in China.    The letters from the House of Representatives and the Minnesota Senate, written by Representative Nels Pierson (R-Stewartville) and Senator Jim Abeler (R-Anoka), were supported by 77 House and Senate co-signers, two of whom are practicing physicians. Both letters expressed concern over Minnesota residents obtaining unethically sourced organs from countries such as China and also mentioned concern over, “…Chinese medical personnel who are trained in Minnesota that may assist in forced organ harvesting.”    The MMA is a non-profit professional association that represents Minnesota physicians, residents, and medical students.    From a Minnesota government press release:    “We need a plan and guideline to prevent anyone from profiting from this horrendous practice in China,” said Sen. Abeler (R-Anoka). “It is vital that we continue to condemn forced harvesting and discourage our citizens from taking advantage of this crime against humanity. Senator Carolyn Laine (DFL-Columbia Heights) declared, “This is a serious human rights issue and we all need to take a vocal stand on this practice.”    The Minnesota legislature has focused on the issue of the persecution and forced organ harvesting from Falun Gong practitioners since 2014. In that year, members of the Minnesota House of Representatives wrote a letter to the Minnesota Department of Health and the Minnesota Office of Higher Education. The letter inquired about any potential collaboration between China and Minnesota regarding organ transplantation.

text: The book is insanely better. The first film of these two sucked so bad. What are these kids so scared of? How many times could "It" have killed them and didn't? Why was it going to take It five hours to rip open that kids stomach in the first flick when they first went into the house? Oh right because It was waiting for the kids friend to come save the day. Someone says Bill Skaarsgard deserves an award. No I think this film series version of It deserves an award for most incompetent killer and dumbest villain ever. The It in the books was far better and the magnitude of the hell he caused over millennia was far more impressive that OF COURSE the losers had to come back to kill it. In this film series It sucks. All of these adults now should have just went on with their lives and maybe a handful of people would have died and probably on account of their own stupidity too because it is incompetent. Now anybody who is like why make negative comments well if this was an original property fine but it's not it's an adaptation of one of my favorite books and it's the equivalent of the directors and actors and every single person involved in this film down to the caterers and coffee fetchers basically saying "this is what we think of the story of It" well this is what I think of the their story of it.

text: I honestly wish that they'd stop remaking the movies, IT chapter one was barely even scary besides the unsettling beginning where Georgie dies (that part only freaked me out because my brother & nephew are around the same age as georgie) and that's kinda it. I remember I sat through the movie in the movie theatre feeling so disappointed while my friend jumped at every single jumpscare. Honestly, Tim Curry's Pennywise scares me more than Bill Skarsgard's (he is a wonderful actor, I will admit that) because Bill's obviously looks off unlike Tim's where you'd probably actually see him at a circus.   After the shitty Pet Semetary remake, I'm either gonna completely sit this one out or wait till it hits redbox because judging from the trailers it's just not going to be for me (extremely shitty, unimpressive, cgi instead of more practical effects).

text: As the losers club is beaten down, scared for their lives, fear gripping their souls providing further fuel for the terrifying clown, a creepy bloody smile etched across his face, the fear further powering the creepy clown. Pennywise, looming over the losers club, instilling fear onto them, the now grown adults backing themselves in the corner, their hearts beating like a machine, fast paced, scared for their lives, Pennywise shape sifting into their deepest darkest fears.  "You can't stop me, I'm fear incarnate." Pennywise said laughing, cackling, the losers club remembering the horrific events that happened in their childhood. As hope seemed to almost be nonexistent, just before it disappeared, a dark gripping voice that instilled fear in criminals spoke from the shadows.  "So you like fear huh?" A voice said in a gritty rough voice.  "Well then you're going to love me." The voice said, jumping out of the shadows, a caped crusader jumping out and punching Pennywise in the face.   "You know why? Because I'm Batman!"

text: I think there's another appearance of the deadlights in the second trailer.  When Adrian Mellon (presumably) is going up and down in the water at around 24-29 seconds of the trailer, you first see a blurry image of a light which seems like it might be light coming in from the tunnel's entrance.  But then when he comes up from the water again, there are two very focused balls of light.  You then see Pennywise again, and then you see one of the balls of light take on a malevolent glow.  It  looks very much like the ball of light the child sees under the bleachers in the first trailer, or the deadlights Beverly see in the first movie when Pennywise splits his head open and puts her into the trance.  We're going to see and learn much more about the deadlights in Chapter 2

text: Everyone is just brilliant and yes, Bill Skarsgård deserves an Oscar, but holy shIT, let's admit that Jackson Robert Scott currently is the best child actor. With only a few scenes featuring Georgie he makes us feel his brother's intense agony of remorse. Feels as if he REALLY was an illusion of pain controlled by Pennywise. And it's not just "It". How can be a kid so talented? I'm definitely going to watch all the films with Jackson. And back to "It", of course I'm ready to sit in the cinema for 3 hours. And for It's sake, I swear to Penny that I'm gonna argue with next person who whines about the film being bad beside the book. I can agree that many films are, well, "not really hitting the point". But not this one. The film will never give the same feeling as the book does, that's true, but "It" is simply a good film. And I'm saying this as a fan of King's horror stories and not really a fan of horror movies.

text: My theory about the scene with a realistic Pennywise at the end is that we aren’t seeing his true identity, but rather the origin of his clown form. In the book it was hinted at that this form was taken from a character called Bob Gray, who may have also been a child murderer. I believe that this scene is showing us the movie’s adaptation of Bob Gray: How he went insane, and then how IT took that shape and likeness.

text: The leader is funny! Do we meet Satan when we cross over? That's what I was thinking 10 years ago. I had this image in my mind of myself as this muscular, huge, Satanic being with huge horns telling the little grays and reptilians following me, "I know...you all come after me. And uh....you should shoot me in the eye!" Then the little grays and reptilians fall onto the ground laughing. I was guided by the aliens to go to this market in Bangkok where I saw this painting of a huge Buddha with all of these little reptilians and other beings pointing their spears at him. Then I saw some paintings of spaceships and I think that these artists were telling me that they believed that we would have a third world war? There were other little clues that I found: a painting of Queen Elizabeth, Mickey Mouse with devil horns, a shirt that said "Leave me alone," and a little squirrel that was chained by the neck inside of it's cage. Despite all my rage I am still just a rat in a cage. Smashing Pumpkins. I think the celebs started the conversation in the chatroom by saying, "Penises and vaginas! We love these things! We love war! I'm Cameron Diaz and I know what it's like to swim freely in the ocean as a dolphin! And I'm Dave Grohl and I know what it's like to be squished as a cockroach! I don't want to look like a stupid clown. I look stupid enough. The aliens can control me to walk to the beat of the music. I notice myself doing this. I stop and then I start doing it again when I do start walking. The aliens controlled me to park next to a nice car for about 3-4 months? I noticed this at some point in my life. The aliens can show me clues using the cars around me. The aliens can control traffic, crowds, and whole cities. I heard that when someone important comes to town in NYC, people feel it. Madonna talked to me about being a part of a studio audience. Aliens use their powers to get everyone to clap in sync with each other. I think the aliens had me speak to a clone of my classmate in 2013. We went to the Mother Clucker's restaurant and there were maybe 10 cops sitting at a table in the corner. I didn't know that this classmate was a clone, but I think that someone may have told me this. She's just weird like that! She goes cross-eyed! I think the stalker has the alien power to make me go cross-eyed. I know I've done this a few times when he's been around. I know that I've stopped breathing when he's around me at the library. I've noticed this while sleeping at home too. There was one night where I lay in bed feeling so scared for some reason. I just kept saying to myself, "Jesus be above me, behind me, and all around me." I said this to myself over and over again and Madonna knew that I had done this. The other kid that was sitting with Mayim Bialik, who was interviewing me during lunch time while the other kids were away, was Troy who looks like the albino hunchback from "The Princess Bride." I think that I spent a lot of time observing him and his best friend, Jessica, who looked like a princess. I think she lived on Palmcroft Lane. Troy always seemed to have a runny nose and he had a nasaly voice. There was a first grader who asked me if I knew what a "reason" was. I had absolutely no idea. I was just in first grade. I have this memory of this guy named Patrick Brennan, who may have been in kindergarten or first grade with me, and in this memory, I am hovering above him and his mother at the grocery store. The other Troy was in another first grade class. I believe that there were 3 classes. I heard that Troy was also at the summer camp after Kindergarten with me. I have no memory of him before high school. I think that Troy may have used his alien powers to change my book report at the last minute to focus on something sexual in "A Brave New World"? I know that I did some kind of last minute change before I went up. Then the teacher said that I should be ashamed of myself and I was kind of shocked. This teacher also called me jello (My Best Friend's Wedding). And this teacher refused to write me a letter of recommendation? I think that she would make disrespectful comments about me to my younger sibling. I went to this teacher's viewing, which was held at the high school. I heard that many people went to one student's viewing. He may have been the first to die in our class. No one told me about this, so I didn't go, but supposedly he raped me. I actually tried to call his mother in 2008. I have many memories of Melanie Middleton. I remember her trying to teach how to pronounce "memo pad," but kept saying "memor" and I told her that it was "meh-mo." I remember seeing her family at McDonald's when I was about 6. My sibling and I were dressed in matching fluorescent yellow outfits. I remember playing Fire Brigade with her and I think she dumped the bucket of water on me or stepped on my toe. I don't remember playing with Brent. I remember having 2 copies of "Mr. Lee's Roses" in the classroom and like 9 copies of the books about aliens, which no one wanted to read.

text: Let me tell you a story about me click of if you don’t care please   When I was younger I loved everything I was innocent and happy and totally oblivious to everything I LOVED scary movies the week before my birthday I decided to watch IT the very first one in 1999 or whatever  that night I got ready with popcorn and my mom put in the cd left the room to get some butter and told me to wait for her I said okay mommy and sat their I touched  nothing the player made a noise and the movie started on it’s on I was already creeped out but I brushed it off that night after i watched the movie it scared the shit out of me that was the day I had my first sleep paralysis I had it multiple times after that night I decided that night I was TERRIFIED of clowns the day of my birthday I was happy I got dressed  and ready for the party I had on  skeleton face paint but like a nice cute beautiful one It was going to be amazing I Just knew I was getting a puppy for my birthday or maybe a pony because I was expecting a surprise (yes I did was a pony and I did get one eventually because my family owns a farm I also have an adorable alpaca ) once I walked out I couldn’t believe what I saw I was HORRIFIED  THERE WAS A CLOWN IN MY BACKYARD  (a female one ) i screamed and ran away my mom came and got me and I eventually got used to the clown she was nice and asked questions and made balloon animals I made an exception to girl clowns maybe they where the nice ones THAT CLOWN RUINED MY BIRTHDAY she asked that day about pets “does everybody  have pets  like maybe a dog?” I got excited maybe. This led to me getting a dog(recently  my grandma and my dog died and my dogs girlfriend had puppies and I wanted something  to remember him as but those were my friends dogs she said I could have some so I Expected that as a birthday gift)  everyone raised their hand except me the clown looked at me and said “well why not?”   I started to tear up And some dumb kid yelled HER STUPID DOG DIED and everybody laughed even the clown  I busted into tears and cried  and ran away  I could hear my mom looking for me but I didn’t want to be found  I turned around and screamed          AW MAN THEIR WAS A CREEPER BEHIND ME it exploded and I lost everything even my trident that was full of enchantments

text: SPOILERS... Just Gonna say: Thank you for Peter Bogdanovich cameo :) You could see McAvoy enjoying that immensely. And watching Bill Hader cry got me SO emotional; was like seeing a family member who's always life of the party, always the binding glue, finally lose it, and out pour the waterworks. Man, Bill Hader TOTALLy Blew me away in this; so so so so happy seeing the comedy master in new territory; much like seeing Jim Carrey in The Majestic, and Truman Show; but not Eternal Sunshine; not a fan of that one. Seeing Jess Chastain and the Ben Hanscom actor reach for each other,  man, THAT Was moving, SO much. How they save each other, through love :) aWwwwWWWWWWWW man! gosh. thank you for this flick. and LOVE James Ransone. He and Bill by the end make SUCH a great duo, of BFFs. Man, they belong in many more movies together, playing buddies; perhaps the next Tarantino. I just wish that pounding music from the trailer was in the movie somewhere. But, regardless, a very satisfying flick, made greater by the perfect casting of each grown-up kid.

text: Hey guys, I just came from movie It 2 and it was awesome. But I want to share with you my unbelievable story, this random stuff happens maybe once in a lifetime so if u are not interested, stop reading. I am from Slovakia and I have a girlfriend named Viktoria (Victoria in english). We saw first chapter one year ago and ever since I've always been talking to her like Pennywise said to Georgie in very first scene "Hi Georgie! Wanna catch a balloon?". But I was saying to her "Hi Viky!" in his voice all the year when we were talking about this movie or just when I wanted to scare her little bit or just for fun. And as I was saying, we were on Chapter 2 today and if you saw it, there was some random girl called Victoria and she was catching this insect (I don't know how it's called in english) and she met Pennywise and guess what!!! He said to her "Hello Vicky!" .............. What are the fu**ing odds that some random girl called Victoria is going to appear in second chapter and "It" will tell her this sh*t which I have been saying to my girlfriend FOR ONE YEAR !!! I just can't believe this, just take all the names in America she could have been named anyhow and that girl couldn't even been there !! I was so excited I was thinking about it all the movie...this will never happen in my life again I swear .. thank you if you read this, sorry for my bad english if I made any mistake .. and please don't hate me, I just wanted to share with you guys this story :))

Also they tuned down the heavy abuse Beverly is going through and her struggles to escape her crazy violent stalking husband and how she deals with her horrible past. And in part 2 she eaven HUGS her rapist daddy and lovingly covers him with a blanket??? Oh c'mon! In part one (and the book) she was completley terrified and repulsed of him and eaven cut her hair when he touched it..in part 1 she almost killed him with the toilet cover as he deserves, and now she hugs him? Bevys sufferings are a very important topic in the book and its it completley played down in this version. Also the part of Bills wife, travelling after Bill and robbed by Pennywise is somehow completley non existent and so his bike Silver never truly can fullfill its purpose in this movie. After seeing this you'll hope another sequel isn't created and also it's as scary as Spacejam and it was boring and a waste of money. Over 2 hours of cheese and the actor who played Pennywise can't act for shit. Only decent but in the entire movie was the queer man getting beaten up at the beginning and threw into a river then Pennywise killing him after that. Then it just drags on and is complex and boring, especially near the end. Few ways to describe IT: CHAPTER 2.... A film that made you wish you were in a coma for over 2 hours, a borefest and incredibly cheesey.

text: I had to say the second IT (IT chapter 2) was really dissappointing… I guess I expect too much - One of the characters was massively underused (i felt like he was going to play a bigger part) - Dont get the hype over bill hader…. he was ok I guess (never really found him that appealing or funny, and Finn's take was much better in my opinion) - Theres too many obvious jumpscares. the first had them too but they were quite expertly handled. Although this one had some well made jumpscares… others were predictable and quite boring… Also was is that hard to think of new monsters? Only the end version seemed new. - very all over the place... too many flashbacks. i get it but it was too much - too much cgi, too much gore (the scary part of the first one was what you didnt see but could predict). The conclusion scene with the kid could have been better handled and they missed a good jumpscare there. - what the hell is with that ending (the way they beat IT)? AM i the only one to think it was lame?? - on that note... what the hell was IT's plan. Was it a grudge?? Oh yeh, lets bring back the group that almost killed me last time!   Still a good movie and the acting was great, IT was also awesome But much worse than the first one.

text: I highly recommend watching this on the big screen. I'm a staunch moviegoer of horror/psychological thrillers and I gotta say It chapter 2  gave me a renewed sense of the genre--while also scaring the fuck out me at times. Much like Insidious, it does well in weaving psychological motifs into a gradient of subtle to overt horror jumpscares. The casting was perfect, from the getgo you really feel the deeply buried trauma the characters carry upon their first gathering. I think book-to-film movies often dilute their original subject material with Hollywood tropes, but Muschietti and Dauberman developed an involved script that had audiences really feel the bond between all of the main characters. TLDR, defiantly watch while it's out in theaters, preferably if you can IMAX or 4DX, you won't regret.

text: This comment has spoilers of the movie. If you haven’t watched IT Chapter 2 and don’t want spoilers, *DO NOT READ.*      So I watched IT Chapter 2 today and for the ending, I was disappointed at the ending. The ending and the origin was more of a sci-fi, which didn’t fit with the movie imo. I didn’t like how at the fortune cookie scene, there was stupid creatures coming out of them. The ritual stuff and the other tribe things were just not fitting for the movie. I know how it’s from the books and all, but it didn’t go well with the movie. And I really wanted to see the part where pennywise jumps on the wall because it looked like a good scene but it didn’t end up in the final production. And the one thing I hate a lot, is at the end where pennywise’s head is smashed flat and there is little baby hands coming out of him, it was just way too goofy for a horror movie and it was similar to the gingerbread man in space movie where one of the people’s heads gets flattened with a pan. That was just the negative things I had to say.   Positive things: I really loved the other part of the movie, it was comedic and horror at the same time. It was also really sad seeing Stan commit suicide and Eddie dying. This is one of the times where when a movie reveals someone is gay, that it is great. I’m not saying I’m homosexual or anything, none of that. It’s just most of those times that happens, it’s like a J.K. Rolling kind of style, it just comes out of the blue and makes no sense. It was sad seeing at the end, Ritchie completing the “R + E” carve where Ben got his stomach carved by Henry and the bullies in chapter 1.  It was sad to me how he married a woman just to show that he “isn’t gay” so people wouldn’t know. Okay, well I think people knew because in one of the scenes, Ritchie is fighting Henry’s little cousin in Street Fighter and when Henry shows up he says that he wants to do gay stuff with him and that and Henry says “Ritchie wants to bone my little cousin?” and Ritchie runs off. I think he married a woman to hide that he was gay so all those “accusations” would look false. I was also sad when Ritchie saw Eddie dying when he gets stabbed my pennywise after saying that he beat him. Ritchie kept making himself believe that Eddie was still able to live, but was wrong.The writing is really good and the jumpscares.   Overall, I give the movie a 9.2/10 I feel like the anticipation was kinda overhyped but I’d say it was worth to wait a while to release. The editing is kinda goofy but most of the movie is just really good. I loved how the movie was 2 hours and 50 minutes, so there was more move time. I think where they should’ve headed in the backstory is that he was a regular clown or something and something evil possessed him or something like that. I didn’t like how it was just that a meteor came down from the sky and there was a demon inside it. I thought that the part where pennywise was like “how poor” (or whatever he says) and where he had makeup coming off his face was from his backstory and not him talking to Beverly. If there was anything you disagreed with me on, you can tell me in the reply section. Anyways, great movie!

text: My rating: 6/5 stars  Yep! "IT" deserves the extra star, imho..! Here's my spoiler free review. Thanks if you take the time to read it ☺  It Chapter 2 follows the Losers' club 27 years after nearly killing Pennywise. The 2nd chapter differs a bit from the book, and the mini series that came out in 1990 (also based on the book).   There is a character twist that is initially subtly hinted, and is finally revealed at the end of the movie (even though the book leaves it ambiguous).  The movie omits any reference to the ancient turtle named Mataurin, and the torrential rain that happens after Pennywise is killed.   But, there's a "Here's Johnny!" reference (from The Shining movie, also based on Stephen King's book). That is quite a surprising bonus scene there, which I love very much.  One scene (the 'thing' that came out of the fridge) is a reminiscent of The Thing (1982), another favourite horror movie of mine.  For me, this is a very satisfying movie. I'm glad that:   • the 2nd chapter avoids delving too much into the two minor characters in the book (Bev's husband and Bill's wife).  • the kid actors have plenty of screen times in this 2nd Chapter. Unlike the mini series, which divided the storylines into two: when they were kids and as adults. • the ending is so satisfying and "realistically" portrayed.. Can't blame the mini series though, probably due to limited budget and technology at that time.   I can relate to all the seven characters (especially Bev, Richie and Eddie) and their childhood experiences. If this were real life, I would have fitted in their Losers' Club perfectly.   Despite already know the ending beforehand, IT Chapter 2 still managed to make me feel very sad.. Watching a horror movie but end up crying? Yep.. That's IT... !!  So, if this is your first time watching it, prepare to feel like your guts have just been ripped out.   The movie is rated R (or 18+ in Msia) for good reasons. Some scenes are quite disturbing for younger viewers.  https://m.facebook.com/story.php?story_fbid=10156514031037157&id=5209721

text: If you've seen the movie, you'll notice a few scenes in this trailer that are missing from the film. Their appearances are abrupt, but they're there. Timestamps are 2:10 and 2:14  The scenes specifically are Bev being held underwater and Mike looking up at Pennywise as he catches his balance on a wall. (Spoiler-ish ahead)   I'm guessing the first scene with Bev would've been when she was grabbed by the old woman and dragged underwater near the end of the film, where the Losers are making their way to the final confrontation with Pennywise. In that scene, where it would've been, all of the Losers except for Eddy go underwater to save Bev, but the camera just stays with Ed, as he just pleads to the group that he wants to be able to make it out, or something. I don't remember what exactly it was he was begging for in the film.   The second one, I don't know. It looks like it would've been Mike's dream/hallucination if he were in the same boat as Ben and Bev when each respectively were pulled into nightmares of their own, Ben being trapped underground in the Losers' hideout, and Bev being drowned by blood in the bathroom. Maybe Pennywise would've brought Mike to The Black Spot, and that's actually what we see in the shot. It's just a guess, though. I know the second one specifically is what it is, but the other is just a guess.

text: Just saw this movie last night and honestly, it was just ok. I couldn’t help but notice that as I was watching it in the theater, I was constantly waiting and yearning for Pennywise to have screen time or for the adults to legitimately be afraid. Don’t get me wrong, the acting and casting was phenomenal; Bill did a phenomenal job once again as Pennywise, hence why I felt disappointed by his lack of scenes. This film just felt too different in comparison to the first....the trailers unfortunately showed off all of the good scares and the Pennywise scenes, making it seem like it’d be similar to the first in terms of sheer tension and horror. That was not the case, as this film steers more in the direction of an adventure film; Pennywise feels more like the mini series Pennywise who is more goofy and comical as opposed to the violent, sadistic and darkly humorous version in the 2017 film.  Until I go for a second viewing, I’m giving it a 7/10.

It was really boring, to say the least!   The ghouls were comical looking, far too many cheesy jokes, the horror scenes were vastly ridicoulous and horrible. I mean, the movie just seemed to not be well thought through. It was a very deplorable screenplay!   Take my advise and do yourself a favor by saving money, and just wait until you can view it in some other way.   I should have just waited until it came out on my free streaming apps, instead of wasting 3 hours of my time and lots of money.  It's just not worth "It!"

text: The movie had a traditional old style forumla concerning the characters but a lot of todays CGI style graphics. The acting and the cinematography was brilliant. However the opening was nonsenscial as were a few other scenes but I can get past that. It was refreshing to view a movie that can be fun and scary without having massive amounts of people being killed by being chainsawed and tortured to dead with bloody body parts flying... It was a horror movie that had a satisfying ending which we seldom see, it's wasn't one of those typical everybody dies or just when you think it's okay it isn't and evil prevails. It had some positive messages including that good can conquer evil and by standing together our strong bonds make us stronger. IT was very refereshing and overall I thought they did a great job to compliment King's book which isn't easy to master.

text: I watched it half way, but end up leaving the theater. It was a good movie...but it wasn't worth my time. I just rather do something more productive. I rather watch this at home while i'm surfing the net. The story alone..it was like the first except the special effects were pretty cool. What I didn't like was how all powerful IT was....I just had a hard time believing it. I have a great imagination....but even this story was too ridiculous to take seriously. And just like the original..like the old tv show or series that was on tv all the time..there are so many characters to the point where I couldn't get attached to any of them and none of them were that charismatic. I enjoyed the first one...but back then, I had no job so I could take it in, but I got a job now and it just seems like a waste of my time. I hope to see it on netflix .

text: You know it's funny. People either really liked this movie, or they really hated it. Well I wouldn't say hate but more disappointed. But there's really no inbetween I've seen.   I mean personally, I thought they did a way better job with the ending than the original. However, I thought the ending was somewhat goofy with Pennywises transformations. I think if he would've stayed as a clown, it would look more real and creepier. I dunno that's just me.   And also some people said this just isn't scary. But do we not understand that horror is subjective? Like something that might not scare you, might scare somebody else. That's the thing I've noticed of the first IT. One of my friends were scared of the disfigured lady, one with the bloody hair in the sink and the other was just scared of the clown. So it might not be scary for you, but it could be terrifying for someone else.   I dunno I just kind of wanted to give my two cents. Cause I've just been thinking about this movie a lot lol.   P.S. That freaking old woman thing is terrifying.

text: I saw people giving 1 star reviews for the pre-order for this movie on Amazon because of "bad language". That's hilarious and too good to be true. Its difficult nowadays for a film to merit an R-rating in today's culture and I think this film did it successfully. Not just with the language but with the scary imagery and the violent bloodiness of the kill scenes. Also there was another who said something along the lines of "Mike is the poor black man who didn't leave Derry. This movie is racist. News Flash! Its 2019!" When I saw that I knew whoever wrote that completely missed the point that Mike was well off in his position and he was an educated "gatekeeper" of the past they shared against IT, should the monster return. The politics of these woke persons just have to seep into entertainment and look for imperfections that simply don't exist, projecting their own hatred of the world onto things that don't warrant that hatred. I'm not saying that IT chapter 2 is a perfect movie, far from it. It is however a sufficient follow up to its predecessor and if you are a fan of the previous film then you're likely to enjoy this, not certainly but likely. Outliers will be outliers, after all it does divert from the context of the book's source material for the film experience. However, it is entertaining when given a fair chance. The climax to how IT is ultimately defeated was the only thing that I probably would have wanted an alternative to. Other than that it was alright for what it was. It is not for the young ones, people going after it for language should really ask themselves what makes them such moral arbiters of upstanding etiquette between adults in reality. Last I checked, adults use profanity when they're among friends. The difference is that when the Losers were in their professional settings before going to Derry, among business associates and people in work, they weren't using profane language. However when they were in good company, among their friends, they were free to talk the way they wanted (especially Richie). Not that it really matters, but most of the Losers Club were not being profane anyway. That's all I have to say about that. Also, rotten tomatoes is a rotten tomato now. No longer accepting critical reviews from that site, the biased is obvious and ridiculous.

text: You know, I think the appeal of the story was that it was just a bunch of kids after this entity. There were no grown-ups to help them or believe them, and they were all by themselves. Just a couple of middle schoolers. Them being adults removes that helplessness of being a child and gives them odd advantages. Besides, isn't it something like "Only children can see Pennywise?" So wouldn't that mean that they wouldn't be able to see him? Finally, why is there still a romance between those two kids? I can understand the whole "middle school sweethearts" thing but they're well into their thirties at this point and have moved on with their lives for the most part, so their little immature romance would long be forgotten right? Or at least make it so they've been married this whole time, and they come back together as a couple. I haven't watched any of the movies and I can still tell this is nothing more than a cash-grab. But, for some unknown reason, Hollywood thinks that cash-grabs don't have to be good or make sense.

text: I watched It Chapter 2 a week ago. It was exactly how I hoped it would be. I might even like it better than the first one, but I only watched it that one time and that may change when I see it again. If you haven't seen the first one, watch that one and then watch this. It's my favorite movie right now. The kids chose the adult cast and they did tremendous. They all look like the first cast and are amazing actors. The humor is also still present. There are a bunch of emotional scenes, too. It's still terrifying. There are a few flashbacks of their younger selves in the movie, and a bunch of the kids hit puberty HARD between 2017 and 2019, and they did a good job using cgi to make them look younger. You need to see this movie if you are a fan of horror, comedy and/or drama.

text: the trailer is what makes it big. it's what brings the attraction. it's what makes you want to watch it over and over and over again. i remember seeing the trailer on tv and thinking to myself, "that looks so fucking good i need to watch it" discussing it with my mom when georgie was saying, "you lied and i died" we thought he was talking to pennywise because she said in the book bill actually had the flu but bill ended up lying to get out of playing with georgie, which is sad .m. but thinking about it i don't care if it was pennywise or bill lying it's just amazing and it's something you never want to miss. i saw this movie on my birthday which was not september 6 and i loved it. many emotions were rushing through me; thrill, sorrow, excitement it was amazing and i don't want to stop watching it. i could care less if I would keep crying every time i watched and saw the pain in richie's eyes, the blood patter on the ground from stanley's bloodstained fingers this movie is my favorite of all the other amazing movies i've seen. i don't care about how many fucking tears i shed each time if i fill a bucket with my tears i know damn well i'm doing it right. andy muschietti constructed these movies amazingly and 100% did NOT disappoint me. the cast did an amazing job pouring out their talents onto the set and into the movie. the actors were chosen carefully and were definitely chosen right because i'm just (i'm reluctant saying this and probably will regret it) an eleven year old that has an attachment to these actors and to these movies when i probably shouldn't be, and i only got startled once or twice watching it and i find that amazing and shocking. i don't know why i'm pouring words onto a screen of my love for this movie but i'm having fun doing it. i'm glad my mom invited me to watch the first it movie with her that... i believe sunday night and watching it because it brought me a new love for movies but it doesn't mean i won't be scared of horror movies anymore. my mom won't let me read the novel but she has her good reasoning but i still want to read it and she says she does have the book in our basement somewhere and in my mind i'm cackling and giggling maniacally. she also said she has vhs tapes of the miniseries in our basement and i'm also excited about that uWu. i'm just a dumb eleven year old with a love for dumb things that i probably shouldn't be but that won't stop me >:3

text: Kid actors in chapter 1 where fantastic and there is also a great chemistry between them. Adult actors (the losers club and Henry Bowers) in chapter 2 are so bad that they don't even look like professional actors and there is no chemistry at all between them. Chapter two also have some of the worst CGI i ve seen in years. CGI kinda reminds me of Xena, The Langoliers, Species and many other 90s movies and series. Andy Muschietti could really do something great here but he prefer to do all the crappy hollywood shit and completely destroy the dark and creepy novel feeling. Although i have to say Bill Skarsgard is excellent and probably without him the movie would flash in the sewers and float down there along with Georgie's hand.
